  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and regulations against money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- An international standard-setting body that develops policies to combat money laundering\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n\n3. The Palermo Convention\n- Provides a framework for international cooperation against organized crime\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision guidelines\n- Sets standards for banks to prevent money laundering\n\n5. Individual countries' anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n- Many nations have specific legislation requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report large or suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include substantial fines and criminal prosecution.",
